    "summary": "The Samanid Empire (819–999 AD) was the first major Iranian dynasty to arise after the Islamic conquest of Persia — a Persian Muslim state centered on Bukhara and Samarkand in Central Asia that governed much of modern Iran, Afghanistan, and Central Asia, and was instrumental in both the revival of Persian language and literature within an Islamic framework and the Islamization of the Central Asian steppes through which Islam would eventually reach the Mongols and Turks. The Samanids governed as nominal vassals of the [[event:2133|Abbasid Caliphate]] while effectively independent.\n\nThe Samanid court was the great patron of New Persian literature — Rudaki, considered the father of Persian poetry, flourished at the Samanid court in Bukhara; the Shahnameh (Book of Kings), the Persian national epic, was begun during the Samanid period (commissioned by the Samanid ruler before being completed under the [[event:2929|Ghaznavid]]) ; and the philosopher-physician [[event:3614|Ibn Sina (Avicenna)]] grew up in the Samanid court environment of Bukhara. The Samanid court library at Bukhara, which Ibn Sina reportedly used, was one of the greatest in the Islamic world. The Samanids were also active in spreading Islam to Turkish nomadic peoples on their northern frontier through trade, missionary activity, and incorporation of Turkish slave-soldiers (ghulam) — creating the military tradition of Turkish Muslim warriors who would dominate Islamic politics from the 10th century onward. The dynasty was overthrown by Turkic Ghaznavid and Karakhanid powers.",
